		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2013"></a><br><code>sle2013/paper14</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2013</a> paper:</span><br><i>A Language Independent Task Engine for Incremental Name and Type Analysis</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/GuidoWachsmuth.html">Guido Wachsmuth</a>, <a href="../profile/GabriëlKonat.html">Gabriël Konat</a>, <a href="../profile/VladVergu.html">Vlad Vergu</a>, <a href="../profile/DannyMGroenewegen.html">Danny M. Groenewegen</a>, <a href="../profile/EelcoVisser.html">Eelco Visser</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-02654-1_15">10.1007/978-3-319-02654-1_15</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagM">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a><ul><li> The primary contribution is incremental name and type analysis—core static-semantics infrastructure for IDE feedback.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> It provides method/tool support (a task engine) intended to be embedded in IDEs to deliver responsive analysis.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> The approach factors analysis into modular tasks with dependencies, emphasizing compositional structuring of analyses across languages.
</li></ul></li></ul>
